Linear Models Procedure

Content:

  1. Explorative Data Analysis (EDA)
  2. Covariates transformations if necessary
  3. Fit a linear model, find significant covariates at \(\alpha = 0.05\) level, and the estimate of error variance \(\sigma\)
  4. Select the best linear model by Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) and the step-wise procedure.
  5. Perform the regression diagnostics for the linear model: R~Age+Ed+Ex0+U2+X. Residual analysis: Plot raw residulas of the fitted linear model against Age and Ed. Plot the internally studendized residuls against the covariates and fitted values. Plot the Q-Q plot to examine the normality assumptions. Compute the hat matrix to find points with high leverage.
Load necessary data set

For data description please check data/Description_USCRIME.txt

# Plot a pairs plot to find dependencies between covariates and the response R
index1 <- c(2:6, 1)
ggpairs(df_uscrime[,index1])

index2 <- c(7:m, 1)
ggpairs(df_uscrime[,index2])

We can see a correlation between \((EX0,R)\); and \((EX1,R)\).

To recall: \(EX\)* represents the police expanditure in 1960 per capita and; \(EX0\) represents the police expanditure in 1959 per capita

This correlation might be intuitive since the higher the crime rate the more the government invest to protect the citizens and to fight to decrease the crime rate but there is also a correlation in \((EX0, EX1)\), this might hint, that investing into police expanditures does not decrease the crime rate immediatelly, i.e.not immediatelly in the next year.

From the plot we can also see high collinearities, e.g.\((U1,U2)\), \((NW,X)\) . This hints, that we do not need all the covariates.

2. Covariates transformations if necessary

We transform all covariates with log and quadratic transformation. And look which trafos are the most suited.

# log trafo
df_uscrime_log <- log(df_uscrime[, 2:ncol(df_uscrime)])
names(df_uscrime_log) <- sapply(names(df_uscrime_log), function(x) paste0(x, "_log"))
df_uscrime_log <- cbind(df_uscrime$R, df_uscrime_log)

# quadratic trafo
df_uscrime_sq <- (df_uscrime[, 2:ncol(df_uscrime)])^2
names(df_uscrime_sq) <- sapply(names(df_uscrime_sq), function(x) paste0(x, "_sq"))
df_uscrime_sq <- cbind(df_uscrime$R, df_uscrime_sq)

log transformation

ggpairs(df_uscrime_log[,index1])

ggpairs(df_uscrime_log[,index2])

squared tranformation

ggpairs(df_uscrime_sq[,index1])

ggpairs(df_uscrime_sq[,index2])

The plots do not hint any improvements, so we do not consider any transformation of covariates.\ However, more robust way would be to fit linear models with possible covariate transformations and\ and then compare R-Squared or to use AIC or BIC.

3. Fit a linear model

Now we fit the linear model

linear_model <- lm(R ~., df_uscrime)

So, significant are only the covariates: Intercept, Age, Ed, U2, X.

To compute the significance the so called Wald test or t-test was used, where the null hypothesis \(H_0\) is that the corresponding coefficient is zero.

The residual standard error is the unbiased estimate of \(\sigma\) and is roughly equal to 21.

# linear_model$sigma
SSE <- sum(linear_model$residuals^2)
n <- nrow(df_uscrime)
p <- length(linear_model$coefficients)
sigma <- sqrt(SSE/(n-p))
print(sigma)
## [1] 21.32298

4. Select the best linear model by Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) and the step-wise procedure.

The Idea is to perform backward step-wise selection with AIC. Then, to perform the forward step-wise selection. Finally, compare both models from both procedure using F-Test or adjusted R-squared.

Backward Selection

lm_full <- lm(R ~., df_uscrime)

lm_reduced <- step(lm_full, direction="backward", scale=0, trace=1)

5. Regression diagnostics

We use here R-base ploting tools. However, consider also the package: ggplot2.

Please consider the linear_regression_appendinx.html to check why for regression diagnostics the residual analysis is used.

Residuals analysis

Raw residuals against the covariates: Age and Education

The following types of plots we could use to find dependencies between covariates and the response.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(df_uscrime$Age, lm_reduced$residuals, ylab="raw residuals", xlab="Age",pch=16)
plot(df_uscrime$Ed, lm_reduced$residuals, ylab="raw residuals", xlab="Education",pch=16)

In both plots we can not see any dependency or systemic error. So, we could state that the covariates does not have any nonlinear influence on the response variable.

Internally studentized residuals

With the following plot we can check the overall model assumptions and also determine possible outliers.

library(ggplot2)
student_res = rstudent(lm_reduced)

df_student <- data.frame(x = 1:nrow(df_uscrime), y = student_res)
ggplot(df_student, aes(x,y)) + geom_point() + geom_text(aes(label=1:nrow(df_uscrime)), position=position_jitter(width=0.5,height=0.5))

We can see that observation 11 might be an outlier, which perhaps needs further investigations. The overall plot looks good.

QQ Plot

qqnorm(student_res, pch=16, cex.lab=1.3, cex.axis=1.3)
abline(0,1)

As we can see the points lie along the idenity line which indicates that the normality assumption is satisfied.

Identyfing high leverage

If an observation indicates a high leverage, it means that the covariates values are outliers w.r.t. other covariate values.

n <- nrow(df_uscrime)
p <- length(lm_reduced$coefficients)

# create the design matrix used to fit the lm_reduced model
X_red <- cbind(rep(1, n) ,df_uscrime$Age, df_uscrime$Ed, df_uscrime$Ex0, df_uscrime$U2, df_uscrime$X)

# compute the hat matrix
H <- X_red %*% solve(t(X_red) %*% X_red) %*% t(X_red)

# extract the diagonal and detect high leverages
h <- diag(H)
high_leverages <- which(h > 2*(p/n))
print(high_leverages)
## [1] 29

So, all covariates are smaller than \(2p/n\), this means there is no high leverage. However, in case we would find an indication of high leverage, then one could graphically investigate if it is really a high leverage in the following way: Plot all posible pairs of covariate (Age vs Ed, Age vs Ex0, ) and in each plot mark the high leverage point. Futrher, examine graphically if it really is an outlier.
